The design of the Personal Finance Tracker emphasizes accessibility and inclusivity to ensure that a wide range of users can effectively interact with the application. Although the program is a command-line interface (CLI), several design choices were intentionally made to reduce barriers and promote usability for individuals with varying levels of technical experience and diverse needs.

First, the application uses a simple, text-based interface with clear prompts and instructions. This design supports users who may not be familiar with graphical user interfaces or advanced software systems. By presenting information in a structured and consistent format, users can easily navigate the menu options and understand how to perform tasks. Clear labeling of options and step-by-step guidance reduces cognitive load and supports users with limited technical literacy (Shneiderman et al., 2016).

Second, the program incorporates error handling to improve accessibility. Input validation ensures that users receive immediate and understandable feedback when errors occur, such as entering non-numeric values for transaction amounts. Instead of crashing, the system provides informative messages and allows users to correct their input. This approach aligns with usability principles that emphasize error prevention and recovery, which are critical for inclusive design (Norman, 2013).

Additionally, the use of plain language throughout the application promotes inclusivity. The program avoids technical jargon and uses straightforward terminology such as “Add Transaction” and “View Summary.” This makes the application more accessible to users from different educational backgrounds and those for whom English may not be their first language.

The application also considers data accessibility by storing information in a JSON format. This format is both human-readable and machine-readable, allowing users or developers to access and interpret the data outside of the application if needed. This transparency supports users who may rely on assistive technologies or alternative methods for interacting with data.

However, it is important to acknowledge current limitations. As a CLI-based program, the application does not yet include features such as screen reader optimization, keyboard shortcuts beyond standard input, or multilingual support. Future improvements could include developing a graphical user interface with accessibility features such as adjustable font sizes, color contrast options, and compatibility with assistive technologies. Additionally, incorporating localization features would make the application more inclusive for non-English-speaking users.

In conclusion, while the Personal Finance Tracker is a simple command-line application, it incorporates several accessibility and inclusivity principles, including clear communication, error tolerance, and user-friendly design. These considerations help ensure that the application can be used by a diverse audience while also providing a foundation for future enhancements in accessibility.
References:
Norman, D. A. (2013). The design of everyday things (Revised and expanded ed.). Basic Books.
Shneiderman, B., Plaisant, C., Cohen, M., Jacobs, S., Elmqvist, N., & Diakopoulos, N. (2016). Designing the user interface: Strategies for effective human-computer interaction (6th ed.). Pearson.
